Fresh-eyes review complete for `src/blog/people/drafts/Benny-Blanco.md` — the notes are appended as a `FRESH EYES REVIEW (2026-07-11)` comment block at the bottom of the file. No body edits were made.

The two biggest issues flagged:

1. **The Selena relationship has no origin story.** The section leans entirely on the internet's "how did he get her" incredulity but never mentions he was her collaborator for nearly a decade first ("Same Old Love" and "Kill Em with Kindness" in 2015, "I Can't Get Enough" in 2019), nor when they actually got together. That history is both a reader expectation and the strongest real rebuttal to the mockery the section catalogues.
2. **His own artist catalog is invisible.** The 2018 artist pivot gets a full section, but no song of his is named except the 2025 Selena album — no "Eastside," no "Graduation," and most glaringly no "Lonely" with Justin Bieber, which is the best on-record proof of the draft's "therapist whose sessions end in songs" thesis. Right now the artist project only exists as a thing critics disliked.

Smaller notes in the block: trim the doubled counter-typing (main body vs. rabbit hole) and the twice-drawn Sheeran "me too" parallel, add one orienting line so the two method sections read as escalation rather than repetition, and consider a beat on the pandemic cooking-video fame. The Stern role-play tiebreaker, the "mmph" bookend ending, and the house-menu conceit are marked as keepers.
